'''Iain Bonomy, Lord Bonomy'''  [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]], [[Queen's Counsel|QC]]  (born 15 January 1946)<ref name = "ICTY">[http://www.un.org/icty/officials/bonomy-e.htm Biography Note Judge Iain BONOMY]</ref> is a [[Senator of the College of Justice]] ([[Inner House]]), a judge of the [[College of Justice|Supreme Courts]] of [[Scotland]]. He was a Judge of the [[International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia]] between 2004 and 2009.

==Early life==
Born on 15 January 1946 in [[Motherwell]], Bonomy attended Dalziel High School and the [[University of Glasgow School of Law|School of Law]] of the [[University of Glasgow]], graduating [[Bachelor of Laws|LL.B.]] in 1968.<ref name = "ICTY" /> In 2006, he was awarded an [[Honorary degree|honorary]] [[Doctor of Laws|LL.D.]] by the University.<ref>[http://www.gla.ac.uk/services/alumni/lifeafterglasgow/ University of Glasgow :: Alumni :: Life after Glasgow]</ref>

He undertook his apprenticeship as a solicitor at [[East Kilbride]] Town Council between 1968 - 1970, before moving into practice with Ballantyne and Copland in Motherwell, rising to become a partner. In 1983, he left to begin [[devilling]], and in 1984 was admitted to the Faculty of Advocates, [[Queen's Counsel|taking silk]] in 1993. From 1990 to 1996, he served as an [[Crown Office and Procurator Fiscal Service#Advocates depute|Advocate Depute]], and in 1996 served as Senior Counsel to the [[Dunblane massacre|Dunblane Inquiry]].

==Judicial career==
In 1997, he was appointed a [[Senator of the College of Justice]], a judge of the [[Court of Session (Scotland)|Court of Session]] and [[High Court of Justiciary]], Scotland's [[College of Justice|supreme courts]], taking the judicial title, '''Lord Bonomy'''. He sat primarily on civil and criminal cases at first instance, although occasionally sat on appellate business.<ref name = "ICTY" /> A tabloid newspaper nicknamed him "Judge Dread" when he jailed a [[heroin]]-dealer for ten years for failing within twenty-four hours to name his supplier.<ref name = "Scotsman">[http://news.scotsman.com/scotland/Scottish-judge-will-oversee-runup.4420717.jp Scottish judge will oversee run-up to Karadzic trial in The Hague]</ref> In 2001, he led a review for the [[Scottish Executive]] of the Practices and Procedure of the High Court; the report, ''Improving Practice - the 2002 Review of the Practices and Procedures of the High Court of Justiciary'' was published in December 2002.

In 2004, he was appointed to the [[International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia]]<ref>[http://www.un.org/icty/pressreal/2004/p838-e.htm Lord Bonomy Appointed as Judge to the ICTY]</ref> (ICTY), sitting as a judge on many high profile cases, and presiding over the trial of former Serbian President [[Milan Milutinovi<U+0107>]]. In August 2008, he was appointed to preside over preparations for the trial of captured former [[Serbs of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian Serb]] leader [[Radovan Karad<U+017E>i<U+0107>]].<ref name = "Scotsman" /><ref>[http://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2008-08-22-3501775267_x.htm UN court assigns Scottish judge in Karadzic case]</ref> He resigned from the ICTY in 2009<ref>[http://www.unhcr.org/refworld/country,,,,SRB,,4a55aea22,0.html Security Council resolution 1877 (2009)]</ref> for personal reasons.<ref>[http://www.icty.org/sid/10203 ICTY Weekly Press Briefing, 20 August 2009]</ref>

He was appointed to the [[Inner House]] of the Court of Session on 16 August 2010<ref>[http://www.scotland-judiciary.org.uk/34/496/The-Right-Hon-Lord-Bonomy-%28Iain-Bonomy%29 Scottish Courts biography]</ref> and appointed to the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]] in October 2010.

